[
    {
        "content": "<p>Okay, it turns out that I was not <em>completely</em> confused about that algebraic integer business... just partially confused.</p>",
        "id": 284093716,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1653630207
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There's a lot of nice information here:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>James S. Milne, <a href=\"https://www.jmilne.org/math/xnotes/Seattle1.pdf\">Motives over finite fields</a>.</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 284093900,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1653630395
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In particular, he classifies simple objects in the category of pure numerical motives.  These are like the pure Chow motives I've been talking about, but defined using an <em>a priori</em> coarser equivalence relation on cycles, called <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adequate_equivalence_relation\">numerical equivalence</a>.</p>",
        "id": 284094187,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1653630787
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The category of pure numerical motives is known to be abelian and semisimple, while for the pure Chow motives in my talk this is still just conjectured.</p>",
        "id": 284094243,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1653630854
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Milne classifies the simple objects in the category of pure numerical motives over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">F</mi><mi>p</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{F}_p</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.975em;vertical-align:-0.2861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">F</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1514em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">p</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2861em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 284094438,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1653631115
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>To do this he defines a <strong>Weil <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span></span></span></span>-number</strong> to be a number whose Galois conjugates, say <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>α</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\alpha</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span></span></span></span> are all such that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi><mi>α</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>p</mi><mrow><mi>k</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">|\\alpha| = p^{k/2}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∣</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span><span class=\"mord\">∣</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0824em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.888em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">/2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> for some <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">k</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span></span></span></span> and also <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>α</mi><msup><mi>p</mi><mi>n</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\alpha p^n </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8588em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is an algebraic integer for big enough <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 284094610,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1653631249
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This is the kind of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>α</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\alpha</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span></span></span></span> we've been talking about, which shows up in the Riemann Hypothesis for finite fields.  But I'm listing more conditions on it now!</p>",
        "id": 284094642,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1653631280
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Anyway, Milne shows that simple objects in the category of pure numerical motives correspond to equivalence classes of Weil <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span></span></span></span>-numbers... where two are equivalent if they're in the same orbit of the absolute Galois group!   (That's what I meant by \"Galois conjugates\" above.)</p>",
        "id": 284094854,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1653631522
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So this is great: it means the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>α</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\alpha</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span></span></span></span>'s I've been talking about, or at least equivalence classes of them, really <em>are the same</em> as the basic building blocks in the world of motives, at least if we use pure numerical motives.</p>",
        "id": 284094945,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1653631596
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So rather than algebraic integers, they are \"algebraic <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span></span></span></span>-ary fractions\" ...</p>",
        "id": 284124060,
        "sender_full_name": "James Deikun",
        "timestamp": 1653653451
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah!   I'd never thought about them before.</p>",
        "id": 284197523,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1653696055
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm learning more about motives from Milne's paper <a href=\"https://www.jmilne.org/math/articles/1994aP.pdf\">Motives over finite fields</a>, and it's really great: way over my head, but full of facts whose <em>statements</em> I at least comprehend.</p>",
        "id": 284234849,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1653752553
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275920\">John Baez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/274877-practice.3A-our-work/topic/motives/near/284094438\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Milne classifies the simple objects in the category of pure numerical motives over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">F</mi><mi>p</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{F}_p</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.975em;vertical-align:-0.2861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">F</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.1514em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">p</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2861em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>To do this he defines a <strong>Weil <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span></span></span></span>-number</strong> to be a number whose Galois conjugates, say <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>α</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\alpha</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span></span></span></span>, are all such that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi><mi>α</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>p</mi><mrow><mi>k</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">|\\alpha| = p^{k/2}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∣</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span><span class=\"mord\">∣</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0824em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.888em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">/2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> for some <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">k</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03148em;\">k</span></span></span></span> and also <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>α</mi><msup><mi>p</mi><mi>n</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\alpha p^n </annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8588em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0037em;\">α</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is an algebraic integer for big enough <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<p>Milne shows that simple objects in the category of pure numerical motives correspond to equivalence classes of Weil <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>p</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">p</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">p</span></span></span></span>-numbers... where two are equivalent if they're in the same orbit of the absolute Galois group!   (That's what I meant by \"Galois conjugates\" above.)</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 284234928,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1653752666
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Actually he does all this assuming the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tate_conjecture\">Tate conjecture</a>.  Wikipedia says:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Like the Hodge conjecture, the Tate conjecture would imply most of Grothendieck's standard conjectures on algebraic cycles. Namely, it would imply the Lefschetz standard conjecture (that the inverse of the Lefschetz isomorphism is defined by an algebraic correspondence); that the Künneth components of the diagonal are algebraic; and that numerical equivalence and homological equivalence of algebraic cycles are the same.</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 284235127,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1653752927
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So we are living in the world of \"conditional results\" I mentioned in <a href=\"https://twitter.com/johncarlosbaez/status/1530229366910619649\">a series of tweets</a> yesterday:</p>\n<div class=\"inline-preview-twitter\"><div class=\"twitter-tweet\"><a href=\"https://twitter.com/johncarlosbaez/status/1530229366910619649\"><img class=\"twitter-avatar\" src=\"https://uploads.zulipusercontent.net/e716f8c3f3ab76851e6edbf6b3d5392e21a713e3/68747470733a2f2f7062732e7477696d672e636f6d2f70726f66696c655f696d616765732f313232343934313337303838353832383630382f4b74617a394a4c425f6e6f726d616c2e6a7067\"></a><p>Mathematicians are a bit nervous about proving \"conditional results\".  What if the conjectures they rely on turn out to be false?   The proofs may still contain useful ideas.   But the glory is gone.   \n\nBut what if civilization collapses before we know for sure?\n\n(6/n)</p><span>- John Carlos Baez (@johncarlosbaez)</span></div></div>",
        "id": 284235148,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1653752980
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But I am struggling to understand the reasoning a bit better, and in particular the role of algebraic integers vs. what <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"438995\">@James Deikun</span> called \"algebraic p-ary fractions\".</p>",
        "id": 284235422,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1653753359
    }
]